<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1448,2015]" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1448,1475]" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of this species are very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Westring, 1861)" authorityName="Westring" authorityYear="1861" baseAuthorityName="Westring" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[778,1151,1449,1476]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Echemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="439" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustifrons">
<emphasis box="[778,950,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">E. angustifrons</emphasis>
(Westring, 1861)
</taxonomicName>
but differ from it by the mushroom-like epigynal frame formed by the widely open lateral margins which connect to the anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[159,290,1521,1547]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–16" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1994,2019]" captionTargetBox="[151,1418,812,1975]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1418,812,1975]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–16. Echemus species: E. kaltsasi sp.n. (13–14), E. levyi (15–16). Left column epigynes, right column vulvae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3351030/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">Figs 13–14</figureCitation>
), in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westring" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[340,511,1521,1547]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Echemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="439" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustifrons">
<emphasis box="[340,511,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">E. angustifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
continuing anteriorly as parallel S-shaped lines and not connecting to the anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[244,361,1557,1583]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–12" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1793,1818]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,561,1774]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,561,1774]" captionText="FIGURES 9–12. Echemus species: E. angustifrons (9–12)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3470819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3470819/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">Figs 9–12</figureCitation>
). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Kovblyuk, 2009" authorityName="Kovblyuk &amp; Seyyar" authorityYear="2009" box="[544,816,1557,1583]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Echemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="439" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="levyi">
<emphasis box="[544,627,1557,1583]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="439">E. levyi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kovblyuk, M. M. &amp; Seyyar, O. &amp; Demir, H. &amp; Topcu, A." box="[634,816,1557,1583]" pageId="5" pageNumber="439" pagination="169 - 187" refId="ref12910" refString="Kovblyuk, M. M., Seyyar, O., Demir, H. &amp; Topcu, A. (2009) New taxonomic and faunistic data on the gnaphosid spiders of Turkey (Aranei: Gnaphosidae). Arthropoda Selecta, 18, 169 - 187." type="journal article" year="2009">Kovblyuk, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger atrium of the epigynal plate and the larger glandular heads of the vulva.
</paragraph>
